UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105021044497?origin=resultslist
AB  - This study objectively evaluates the carbon footprint and environmental sustainability of Northport, a crucial maritime trading centre in Port Klang, Malaysia, emphasizing alignment with the nation's Net Zero Port 2050 objective. The study assessed the environmental impact of port operations from human factors by analysing carbon absorption capacity, water consumption indicators, and waste management efficiencies. Data were thoroughly gathered and analysed on terminal visiting patterns, CO2 emissions, and vegetative cover from 2021 to 2023, employing spatial analysis and advanced statistical modelling. Our research demonstrates that Northport's green infrastructure, encompassing 33.37 hectares of varied flora, has the capacity to sequester 17,435.73 tons of CO2 each year, predominantly due to tree canopy coverage. Nonetheless, waste recycling rates remain inadequately low, with a decline from 1.45% in 2021 to 0.82% in 2023, indicating the need for effective waste diversion strategies. Furthermore, inefficiencies in water utilization were identified, underscoring problems in resource management. This paper offers recommendations to enhance Northport's environmental framework, addressing critical challenges in waste management, carbon reduction, and resource efficiency. By implementing these efforts, Northport might serve as a model for international ports, supporting Malaysia's strategic goal of achieving Net Zero by 2050, so integrating operational efficiency with sustainable development. © School of Engineering, Taylor’s University.
