UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/85075080305?origin=resultslist
AB  - Flinders Ports' Adelaide Container Terminal (FACT) is South Australia's only container terminal. Constructed in 1977, the terminal is subject to continually increasing operational demands. The lack of consistent and useable data on the site, combined with significant and increasing maintenance burdens, hampered current and future planning at the terminal. Between June and November 2018, Jacobs, with Flinders Ports, designed and executed an innovative survey and pavement assessment program, delivering a comprehensive and interactive dataset to inform current and future decision making. The project aims were: 1. Reduce operational disruption and exposure of personnel to the dangers of a terminal environment 2. Provide a comprehensive assessment of current pavement condition and maintenance priorities 3. Provide a rich dataset to assist with future planning and projects 4. Deliver in a format readily accessible to a range of stakeholders Jacobs applied experience from Webb Dock and the Port of Burnie to combine cutting edge mobile laser scanning technology and orthorectified imagery (captured via remotely piloted aircraft) to produce a detailed 3d model of the container terminal. A virtual site inspection was conducted on the resultant, rich data set. Defects were heat mapped using a digital straight edge, pavement slope, and semi-automated photogrammetric crack detection. Major defect classes present in the pavement were identified, classified and prioritised for rectification. All data was delivered via an interactive GIS webmap, accessible to all Flinders Ports personnel. The data was also arranged to facilitate integration into Flinders Ports' GIS system. The project shows that with collaboration and an understanding of the required outcomes, the application of emerging technology can provide outcomes not previously possible in the port environment. The richness and accuracy of data provides flexibility for condition benchmarking and future planning combined with the ability to investigate and assess issues not considered at the time of inspection. © Australasian Coasts and Ports 2019 Conference. All rights reserved.
