UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105002003668?origin=resultslist
AB  - Traditional machine learning methods using Automatic Identification System data struggled with data unreliability and failure to capture spatial relationships. To address these challenges, a novel prediction method combining fine-grained origin-destination matrices and a Spatial-Temporal Zero-Inflated Negative Binomial Graph Neural Network for port navigation networks was proposed. Vessel traffic's spatial-temporal characteristics and topological structure were analyzed, with a sparsity parameter π incorporated to manage uncertainty and sparsity. Tested on Qiongzhou Strait port group data, the model was shown to outperform four benchmarks—Spatial-Temporal Negative Binomial Graph Neural Network, Spatial-Temporal Gaussian Graph Neural Network, Spatial-Temporal Graph Convolutional Network, and the Historical Average model—across three temporal resolutions. At a one-day resolution, a mean Kullback–Leibler Divergence of 0.035, a root mean square error of 0.244, and a mean absolute error of 0.183 were achieved, with narrow confidence intervals averaging 0.075. These results demonstrated superior accuracy and robust uncertainty quantification. This method was found to enhance vessel traffic prediction, supporting improved safety and management in waterway navigation networks. © 2025 Elsevier Ltd
