AB  - Autonomous Underwater Vehicles (AUVs) are critical in maritime operations, making the development of intelligent game strategies essential. While multi-agent deep reinforcement learning (MADRL) holds promise for game decision-making, its deployment is limited by the simulation-to-reality (Sim2Real) gap. Direct field testing, meanwhile, is costly and inefficient. To address these issues, this paper presents a Sim2Real-capable MADRL framework for AUV games, incorporating hierarchical decoupling and implicit constraint learning to enhance strategy generalization and transferability. Additionally, an interaction-driven digital twin system is developed to synchronize virtual and physical parts, enabling low-cost, high-confidence strategy validation. Lake trials in pursuit-evasion and attack-defense games validate the proposed method's practicality, enabling the Sim2Real transfer of AUV game strategies. © 2025 The Authors. This is an open access article under the CC BY-NC-ND license.
