VL  - 280
C7  - 112165
DO  - 10.1016/j.comnet.2026.112165
UR  - https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105032087971?origin=resultslist
AB  - Mobile edge computing (MEC) provides low-delay and high-bandwidth services for Internet of Things (IoT) devices by bringing cloud computing capabilities closer to the network edge, effectively alleviating the resource limitations of terminal devices. However, MEC has limited coverage and is susceptible to obstruction by obstacles in practical deployments, leading to degraded communication quality or even service interruptions for some users. The simultaneously transmitting and reflecting reconfigurable intelligent surface (STAR-RIS) expands the coverage range of MEC by reconfiguring the wireless transmission environment and enabling terminals to communicate with the access point (AP) through either transmission or reflection regions. However, real-time acquisition of network information and unified management of devices in STAR-RIS-assisted MEC still pose challenges. The digital twin edge network (DITEN) provides advantages in resource scheduling and network state monitoring by constructing virtual replicas of physical systems. In this paper, under the DITEN framework, we investigate the task offloading and resource allocation problem for STAR-RIS-assisted MEC, aiming to achieve low-delay services through hierarchical design and joint optimization. Specifically, based on users’ relative positions to AP and STAR-RIS, we classify them into three categories and formulate differentiated offloading strategies accordingly. Building on this, we establish a joint optimization problem that encompasses task offloading, communication and computation resource allocation, and STAR-RIS parameter configuration, which comprehensively considers the end-to-end (E2E) process of local computing, task offloading, result uploading, and edge computing. To address the non-convexity of the problem, we adopt a problem decomposition and alternating optimization mechanism, combining methods such as semidefinite programming and inner convex approximation to efficiently solve it. Simulation results demonstrate that the proposed joint optimization algorithm outperforms benchmark schemes in reducing E2E delay, validating the effectiveness of the collaborative optimization strategy of DITEN and STAR-RIS in MEC. © 2026 Elsevier B.V.
