AB  - Palabuhanratu seaport is not yet operational due to several land facilities still to be constructed and a poorly performing port basin. The offshore facilities consist of a jetty and a breakwater. During the construction of the breakwater, a tombolo formed; a tombolo being a natural tongue of land or a spit formed by deposition. In this case, sedimentation in the tombolo became much worse during the construction of the jetty, continuing up to the end of the project. Nowadays, the port basin is nearly parallel to the pier, while the elevation values in front of the pier range between +0.8 and +2.5 meters LWS. The objective of the study is to explain the sediment transport processes that lead to a tombolo formation, regarding construction sequences. A simple simulation of sediment movement will be developed using the backtracking analysis. The spatial analysis indicates the changes of the shoreline during and after the construction periods; up to a remarkable 65.69% area of change from June 6 to September 16, 2018. Hydro-oceanographic simulations showed significant bed level changes around the site, with bed elevations up to 3.4 meters of sedimentation on the left bank and 3.0 meters of erosion on the right bank. These findings have shown shallow conditions in the seaport basin of Palabuhanratu, indicating that the sediment transport is cross-shore, which is perpendicular to the coast. These have disrupted the pre-existing balance of longshore sediment transport at the ports, which then resulted in significant sediment deposition compromising the depth and functionality of the port basin. © 2025 Institute of Physics Publishing. All rights reserved.
