AB  - In smart ports, the environment of berthing and unberthing processes is complex, often involving multiple ships. To ensure the safety and efficiency of ships and ports, it is essential to accurately obtain the spatial distribution characteristics between the berthing ship and surrounding ships. Therefore, this paper proposes a spatial state analysis method for the berthing and unberthing process under multi-ship data. This method has three main steps. Firstly, combining the GIS regional model theory with the main direction calculated using the principal component analysis (PCA) method, a regional model with rotational angles and equal lengths is constructed to describe the shape of point cloud data and analyze the spatial motion state. Secondly, according to spatial state measurement indicators including Euclidean distance, spatial overlap degree, and direction angle, the spatial relationship between multiple ships is measured to obtain the spatial distribution characteristics during the berthing and unberthing process, and then the key parameters are given. Thirdly, the spatial distribution pattern of the ship during berthing and unberthing under multi-ship data is displayed by utilizing the spatial autocorrelation method. Taking the ships during the berthing and unberthing process at Dalian Port in China as the experimental objects, the collected data validated the feasibility of this proposed method, which can provide an effective spatial analysis tool for monitoring berthing and unberthing operations. © 2024 Elsevier Ltd
